Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Boil a full #kettle{}.

Pop the @diced sweet potato{200%g} onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden and tender, ~{18-20%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

In the meantime, pour the boiled water from your kettle into a large #saucepan{} with @salt{1/4%tsp} on high heat.

Add the @basmati rice{150%g} and cook for ~{10-12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pan. Cover with a #lid{} and leave to the side until ready to serve.

While the rice cooks, peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Zest and halve the @lime{1}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the garlic, @tomato puree{30%g} and @Cajun spice mix{1%portion}. Cook until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Lower to medium heat, then add the @water{100%ml} and @vegetable stock paste{15%g}. Simmer until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine the @soured cream{75%g} and lime zest.

Add the @peas{120%g}, cooked rice, @honey{15%g} and @butter{20%g} to the frying pan. Stir to combine.

> TIP: IF your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

Once roasted, stir the sweet potato through the spicy rice. Squeeze in the juice from half the lime. Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed.

When ready, share the spicy rice between your #bowls{}.

Crumble over the @Greek style salad cheese{50%g} and top with a dollop of zesty soured cream.

Serve with any remaining lime cut into wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!